@startuml sequence_git_timeout
!theme plain
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title GitSync — Git Command Timeout & Injection Safety

participant "GitService" as GIT
participant "GitProcess\nRunner" as RUNNER
participant "git (process)" as GIT_EXE

== Timeout Scenario ==

GIT -> RUNNER : RunAsync(opts)\nTimeout = 30s

RUNNER -> RUNNER : ProcessStartInfo:\n  UseShellExecute = false\n  ArgumentList = args\n  RedirectStdout/Stderr

RUNNER -> GIT_EXE : process.Start()

RUNNER -> RUNNER : var timeoutCts =\n  CancellationTokenSource(timeout)\nvar linkedCt =\n  CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinked\n  (timeoutCts, outerCt)

RUNNER -> RUNNER : Task.WhenAny(\n  process.WaitForExitAsync(linkedCt),\n  timeoutTask)

note over GIT_EXE
  git hangs (e.g. network stall
  during push to unreachable remote)
end note

RUNNER -> RUNNER : timeoutTask fires after 30s

RUNNER -> GIT_EXE : process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true)

RUNNER --> GIT : GitCommandResult\n{ ExitCode=-1, TimedOut=true }

GIT -> GIT : Log Warning\n"git {cmd} timed out after {timeout}"
GIT --> GIT : return result\n(caller skips remaining steps)

== Injection Safety Scenario ==

GIT -> RUNNER : RunAsync with args:\n  ["commit", "-m",\n   "; rm -rf / #"]

note right of RUNNER
  ArgumentList is used — each element
  is passed verbatim as a separate
  argument. The shell never sees it.
  UseShellExecute = false ensures
  cmd.exe / sh is NOT invoked.
end note

RUNNER -> GIT_EXE : git commit -m "; rm -rf / #"
note right of GIT_EXE
  git receives the literal string
  "; rm -rf / #" as the commit
  message. No shell command runs.
end note

GIT_EXE --> RUNNER : exit 0 (commit created)
RUNNER --> GIT : GitCommandResult { ExitCode=0 }

@enduml
